          <!-- IELTS Test Format -->
          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>IELTS Test Format</h2>
            <p>Here’s an overview of what format you can expect and what you need to prepare while appearing for an IELTS exam.</p>
            <h3>IELTS Reading</h3>
            <p>The IELTS reading test has 40 questions divided into 3 parts. Each section has a single text and a set of questions. Each section should take about 20 minutes to complete.</p>
            <h4>Question Types:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Multiple choice</li>
              <li>Identifying information</li>
              <li>Matching information</li>
              <li>Sentence completion</li>
              <li>Summary completion</li>
              <li>Diagram labeling</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IELTS Writing</h3>
            <p>The IELTS Writing test lasts 60 minutes, and you’ll have to complete two writing assignments, each with a different form of text (description, report, discussion, argument, opinion text).</p>
            <h4>Tasks in the Academic Format:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Task 1: Describe or summarize a graph, table, chart, or diagram.</li>
              <li>Task 2: Write a formal essay expressing your point of view.</li>
            </ul>
            <h4>Tasks in the General Training Format:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Task 1: Write a personal, semi-formal, or formal letter.</li>
              <li>Task 2: Write a personal-style essay expressing your opinion.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IELTS Listening</h3>
            <p>The IELTS listening test is divided into four sections, with each section having a unique theme or emphasis. Each recording is played only once, and test-takers are allowed to take down notes while listening.</p>
            <h4>Question Types:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Multiple choice</li>
              <li>Matching</li>
              <li>Diagram labeling</li>
              <li>Sentence completion</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IELTS Speaking</h3>
            <p>The IELTS Speaking test is a face-to-face interview with an examiner and is divided into three parts:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Part 1: Introduction and questions on familiar topics.</li>
              <li>Part 2: A one-minute preparation followed by a two-minute speech.</li>
              <li>Part 3: A discussion on abstract ideas.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <!-- IELTS Exam Pattern Subject Wise -->
          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>IELTS Exam Pattern 2024 Subject Wise</h2>
            <p>Each section of the exam evaluates your language skills, and the IELTS exam syllabus is divided into four parts. Here’s a detailed overview of the four sections of the IELTS exam pattern:</p>
            <h3>IELTS Listening</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Duration: 30 minutes, 40 questions in 4 sections.</li>
              <li>Sections: Everyday conversations, monologues, academic dialogues, and lectures.</li>
              <li>Question Types: Multiple choice, matching, form completion, diagram labeling, sentence completion, etc.</li>
              <li>Scoring: Band scale from 0 to 9.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IELTS Reading</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Duration: 60 minutes, 40 questions across 3 sections.</li>
              <li>Format: 3 passages with 13-14 questions each.</li>
              <li>Question Types: Multiple choice, identifying information, matching information, sentence completion, summary completion, diagram labeling, etc.</li>
              <li>Scoring: Band scale from 0 to 9.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IELTS Writing</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Duration: 60 minutes.</li>
              <li>Tasks: Two tasks (Academic: Describe a graph/diagram and write an essay; General Training: Write a letter and an essay).</li>
              <li>Scoring: Band scale from 0 to 9.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IELTS Speaking</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Duration: 11-14 minutes, 3 parts.</li>
              <li>Parts: Introduction, long turn, and discussion.</li>
              <li>Scoring: Band scale from 0 to 9.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <!-- IELTS Exam Scoring Pattern -->
          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>IELTS Exam Scoring Pattern</h2>
            <p>The IELTS exam pattern uses a 9-band scale to clearly define a candidate’s English proficiency levels. For each test component – listening, reading, writing, and speaking – a score will be assigned first. After that, the individual ratings will be averaged and rounded off to arrive at an Overall Band Score (OBS).</p>
            <div class="highlight-box">
              <table>
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Band Score</th>
                    <th>Skill Level</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td>9</td>
                    <td>Expert user</td>
                    <td>Has fully operational command of the language: appropriate, accurate, and fluent with complete understanding.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>8</td>
                    <td>Perfect user</td>
                    <td>Has fully operational command of the language with only occasional unsystematic inaccuracies and inappropriacy.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>7</td>
                    <td>Good user</td>
                    <td>Has operational command of the language, though with occasional inaccuracies, inappropriacy, and misunderstandings in some situations.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>6</td>
                    <td>Competent user</td>
                    <td>Has generally effective command of the language despite some inaccuracies, inappropriacy, and misunderstandings.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>5</td>
                    <td>Modest user</td>
                    <td>Has partial command of the language, coping with overall meaning in most situations, though is likely to make many mistakes.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>4</td>
                    <td>Limited user</td>
                    <td>Basic competence is limited to familiar situations. Has frequent problems with understanding and expression.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>3</td>
                    <td>Extremely limited user</td>
                    <td>Conveys and understands only general meaning in very familiar situations. Frequent breakdowns in communication occur.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>2</td>
                    <td>Intermittent user</td>
                    <td>No real communication is possible except for the most basic information using isolated words or short formulae in familiar situations.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>1</td>
                    <td>Non-user</td>
                    <td>Essentially has no ability to use the language beyond possibly a few isolated words.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>0</td>
                    <td>Did not attempt test</td>
                    <td>No accessible information provided.</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- FAQs -->
          <section class="content-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)</h2>
            <h3>What is the IELTS exam pattern?</h3>
            <p>The IELTS exam pattern consists of four sections: Listening (30 minutes), Reading (60 minutes), Writing (60 minutes), and Speaking (11-14 minutes). It lasts 2 hours and 45 minutes.</p>
            <h3>Is 7 easy to get in IELTS?</h3>
            <p>Scoring a 7.0 in IELTS is achievable with strong preparation. It indicates that you are a “Good User” with a high level of proficiency.</p>
            <h3>Is 7.0 enough for IELTS?</h3>
            <p>A 7.0 is considered a good IELTS score and is accepted by most universities. However, specific programs may demand higher scores.</p>
            <h3>Is 7.5 IELTS good?</h3>
            <p>A 7.5 in IELTS is a very good score and represents high proficiency in the language.</p>
            <h3>Is 6.5 a bad IELTS score?</h3>
            <p>A 6.5 in IELTS is not bad and is a minimum score requirement in most universities.</p>
          </section>
